Multiple sclerosis: it's not just the medication that matters, it's the patient's will to fight.
Multiple sclerosis is a complicated disease and a person with this diagnosis needs the care of a number of professionals: neurologist, physiotherapist, ergotherapist, urologist, ophthalmologist, psychologist, psychiatrist and many other specialists.
However, it is not only about medical care, for example, women with multiple sclerosis need consultations if they decide to have a child, care for these patients includes social legal advice, recommendations for housing treatment, etc.
Yet all of this is not enough: the development of the disease can be fundamentally influenced by the patient himself.
The more he actively fights the disease, the longer he can work and do not have to fundamentally change the style of his life.
As doctors point out, the patient’s passivity frees space for disease activity.
For example, regular movement is shown to significantly delay the time when the patient needs a compensatory aid, such as a stick.
It is important that patients and their surroundings are not subject to different myths, such as that the disease automatically leads them to end up in a wheelchair.
That's why the Give a Chance page was created (www.bezmytu.cz), which is supported by the ongoing media campaign Give a Chance.
The most important person in the care of the sick with multiple sclerosis is the neurologist.
In multiple sclerosis, there is a saying twice that the sooner the disease starts, the more likely something the doctor can influence.
It is because we have medicines for multiple sclerosis in an inflammatory stage when the process of neurodegeneration is not yet so strong.
The sooner we intervene, the greater the hope that we will be able to stop and delay disability, explains MUDr. Eva Medová from the Neurological Clinic of the General Faculty Hospital in Prague.
It is very important in people with multiple sclerosis rehabilitation care, which most often solves weakening of the lower limbs or disorder of balance.
Patients are treated according to their individual needs: to maintain fitness, improve gait, strengthen pelvic floor, relieve swallowing disorders or improve coordination.
"It is really individual, depending on the specific problems of the patient," says MUDr. Martina Kövári, head of the Department of Rehabilitation and Physical Medicine of the University Hospital in Motol.
People with multiple sclerosis suffer from the same disease, but it is manifested in a slightly different way for everyone.
Rehabilitation can't stop the disease, but it can always relieve its symptoms.
Movement activity, however, also strengthens the immune condition of the organism, which is desirable in the case of multiple sclerosis.
Another positive of regular exercise is the fact that the sick are verifying what they can do, and that strengthens their confidence.
"The endorphins are also washed out during the exercise and you feel good about it," warns PhDr. Kamila Řásová of the Clinic of Rehabilitation Medicine of the Royal Vinohrady University Hospital.
By influencing the physical side, we act on the limbic system responsible for emotions.
We directly interfere with the psyche and immune processes and stabilize the disease, adds.
"These patients were previously spared, today we know that they need a targeted burden," says Professor PaedDr. Pavel Kolář, head of the Department of Rehabilitation and Physical Medicine of the University Hospital in Motol.
Physiotherapy is intended to enable a person to remain self-sufficient for as long as possible, including work assignments.
Physiotherapists therefore work with ergotherapists to get each person a compensation aid tailored to him.
Many patients also need the care of a psychologist or psychiatrist.
They're in a difficult situation.
When a serious illness comes into your life, it usually shakes people.
They're in shock, panic, fear.
They must respond to a great burden - loss of health.
With a sore soul like this, we're supposed to go to someone, not try to take everything on our own shoulders.
"I work with them in such a way that they eventually conclude that even with a handicap you can live a full life and that multiple sclerosis does not mean the end of life," says psychotherapist Renata Malinová - Schubertová of the Neurological Clinic of the General Faculty Hospital in Prague.
