"Sonogenics" or "brain cell control" using sound waves
This video shows how sound impulses affect the direction the nematodes move.
Scientists raised worms with a genetically modified nervous system that can control sound waves.
The tiny nematodes change direction when they are hit by sound impulses that are inaudible to the human ear.
Pulses work by switching cells of genetically modified motor neurons that are programmed to react to these ultrasonic waves.
Related: Scientists can read and write brain activity with light
Scientists have said that these worms are a great example of a new methodology called sonogenics, which uses ultrasound to activate brain, heart, and muscle cells and activates outside the body.
Sreekanth Chalasani, a researcher at the Salk Institute in La Jolla, California, told the Guardian that one day this method could replace deep brain stimulation - an invasive procedure in which electrodes that stimulate the brain are injected into the patient’s brain.
The tubers usually do not respond to ultrasound, but the Chalasani found that the reaction occurs when they are placed in a fluid containing microscopic bubbles.
As he discovered, the bubbles amplify the ultrasound waves, which then pass through the worm's body.
The amplified ultrasound waves act in the ion channels TRP-4, which is located in the membranes of some worm cells.
Thanks to sound waves, these channels open and activate the cells they are associated with, reports Nature Communications magazine.
In order to control the nematodes using ultrasonic waves, Chalasani genetically modified the worms so that some of their motor neurons contain TRP-4 ion channels.
When he then used ultrasound on such modified worms, the sound waves were reinforced by microbubbles and transferred to worms, where modified motor neurons were switched on.
In many ways, the new method resembles optogenetics, a pioneering tool that enables scientists to turn neurons on and off with light.
Chalasani, however, let himself be heard that sonogenics could have many advantages over this technique.
Unlike light, which must be sent by optical fiber to the desired place in the brain, ultrasonic waves can penetrate the tissues without restriction and be sent directly to the brain.
"We believe that if we use gene therapy and therapeutic viruses, we can target human neurons and make them temporarily sensitive to ultrasound signals used in clinical treatment to treat neurological diseases," Khalasani said.
He added that the method would also find its application in the treatment of muscle cells and insulin-producing cells.
