Xi calls for the opening up of the economy to the wider world
It is necessary to open up the economy to a wider world to boost growth, said President Xi Jinping to a group whose task is to reform management on Tuesday.
"China should be involved in attracting foreign investment and expertise and improving open policies," he said on the 16th session of the Central Head of the Group to deepen the overall reform.
Promotion of opening up in emerging reforms will give new impetus and vitality, also providing new space for economic growth, says Xi.
The lead group has adopted a number of directives, including a negative list of regulatory access to the market, the release of border control policy, the promotion of state-owned enterprises (SOE) to absorb private capital and the reorganisation of the registered resident system.
The declaration states that a negative list will be drawn up identifying sectors and enterprises that are outside the investment limits.
This system will be gradually tested and improved through test programmes.
This step is important because it will give the market a greater role in resource allocation, ensuring a legal business environment and making the market more open, stating the statement.
The government will also release controls on the powers it delegates to companies and make sure that companies themselves decide how to run their business.
The statement also states that China will allow border areas to discover new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms to promote regional growth.
In an effort to open up the state-controlled sector, more areas will be open to private investment.
"The government will not change its policy towards foreign investment and will protect the legal interests of companies that are funded from abroad and will provide them with better services," the statement states.
Moreover, it will be easier for foreigners to apply for a permanent residence permit or a "green card" by optimizing the requirements and simplifying the application process.
Ensuring the rights of lawyers to practice and develop professional judges and prosecutors were also discussed at the meeting.
The meeting was also attended by Prime Minister Li Keqiang and leaders Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli, according to a statement issued after the meeting.
A new bed department may be established in the Karlovy Vary Region.
According to Deputy Governor of the Karlovy Vary Region Jakub Důšek (ČSSD), the current capacity of bed departments of two regional hospitals and two private hospitals in the region is sufficient and partial adjustments should be made on the basis of an agreement between the departments of individual hospitals.
In the region, however, there are also possibilities to extend care.
For example, the surgical department could develop a one-day surgery centre where surgical procedures that do not require hospitalization for more than 24 hours would be performed according to the established concept.
It is not yet clear in which specific hospitals the one-day surgery workplace should be in.
A laser center with the possibility of using laser technology for skin diseases could be developed at the skin department of the Karlovy Vary Hospital.
The concept also recommended the emergence of an apalic center that would take care of patients with brain problems who are in a vegetative state.
Such a centre should be centrally established and should be an integral part of the anesthesiology-resuscitation department.
There is also the possibility of concentration of such facilities to the island hospital, where similar care already exists.
Another bed capacity, which appears to be insufficient in the Karlovy Vary Region, is the subsequent care beds, in particular the beds of Léčeben long-term patients (LDN), whose capacity in Nejdek is insufficient and, above all, should be closely linked to acute care beds.
Part of this device should function as beds rehabilitation and part as classic LDN beds, recommends conception.
As he points out, the beds of follow-up care are mainly missing in the Karlovy Vary hospital.
There you could use abandoned buildings after centralization.
Last but not least in the Karlovy Vary Region, social health beds with a focus on the treatment of Alzheimer's disease are absent.
These beds are scarce throughout the Republic, so they could also serve for other regions as the so-called Alzheimer's Center.
According to the recommendations, hospitals should also prepare for the introduction of so-called successive beds, for which European funding will be released.
"These are beds that will be linked to the areas of supespecialized care and will create room for translation of patients after surgery, e.g. after cardiosurgery, neurosurgery, transplantation or other surgery," the regional concept describes.
New services could also be offered in the area of psychiatric care.
